\chapter{Resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}}
\label{chap:resource_intensity}
%#############################################################
%\epigraph{The conservation of natural resources is the fundamental problem.
% Unless we solve that problem it will avail us little to solve all the others.}
%{Theodore Roosevelt}
\epigraph{Without natural resources, life itself is impossible. From birth to 
death, natural resources, transformed for human use, feed, clothe, shelter, and
transport us. \ldots
% Upon them we depend for every material necessity, comfort, convenience, and protection in our lives.
Without abundant resources, prosperity is out of reach.}
{Gifford Pinchot}

The previous chapter addressed the sustainability implications of 
economic affluence, the \mft{A} term in the IPARX equation (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}, 
repeated below for convenience). 
Because the economy is society's metabolism, economic growth and increasing affluence
mean increasing use of natural resources. 
This chapter explores the sustainability implications of resource acquisition and consumption, 
which are reflected in the \mft{R} variable.

\begin{equation} 
  \iparx            \tag{\ref{eq:IPARX}}
\end{equation}

Whether we are aware of it or not, 
all plant, animal, and human life on Earth depends on natural resources, 
provisioned by the ecosystem. 
(See Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.)
Where would you be without air and water to breathe and drink?
Without minerals to make cars?
Without timber to build homes?
Without healthy soil to grow food?
Without oceans and atmosphere to accept wastes?
Without coal, oil, and methane to make electricity, gasoline, and natural gas?
Nowhere.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Definitions}
\label{sec:resource_intensity_definitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


%..............................
\paragraph{Intensity}
%..............................

An intensity is like an efficiency, except the numerator and denominator have 
different units.
A furnace that burns a quantity of natural gas that releases 100 BTUs of heat might
only deliver 96 of those BTUs to your house.
Such a furnace has an \emph{efficiency} of 96\% (BTUs delivered per BTUs input);
see Section~\ref{sec:heating_and_cooling}.
for more on furnace efficiency and a related metric,
Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE).)
A natural gas power plant might burn gas at a rate that releases 300 MW of heat to generate
100 MW of electricity. 
Such a power plant has an efficiency of 33.3\%.
In both cases, the input and output have the same units of energy, BTUs for the furnace
and MW for the power plant.
In contrast, an \emph{intensity} has \emph{different} units
for input and output.
A vehicle's fuel economy, measured in miles per gallon, is an intensity.
Carbon emissions per ton of freight per mile moved is an intensity.
It is \emph{intensive} because total carbon emissions depend on the tons
moved or the total km traveled.


%..............................
\paragraph{Primary vs. Final}
%..............................

Imagine a coal-fired power plant that generates electricity to charge
an electric car. 
Coal is the \emph{primary} energy source. 
The electricity sold to consumers is considered to be a \emph{final} energy carrier.%
\footnote{
  Note that the term ``final'' comes from economics,
  where electricity purchases by consumers are 
  counted in ``final demand.''
}
%
Hydro, solar, and wind are primary energy sources. 
So are coal, crude oil, and methane.
In contrast, gasoline is a refined fuel. 
As such, it is the \emph{product} of 
a refinery that converts crude oil to refined fuels. 
Likewise, natural uranium is a primary energy carrier that must be converted into 
fissionable uranium fuel before it can be used in a nuclear power plant to generate electricity.
The oil refinery or nuclear-fuel enrichment process can be evaluated for their
energy return on investment (EROI); 
see Section~\ref{sec:masterE}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Resources}
%..............................

We define a \emph{resource} as a primary input to the economy. 
As such, a resource is something \emph{extracted} from the natural world.
It is something provisioned by the ecosystem, to use the language 
of Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.
Timber is a resource. Iron ore is a resource. Water is a resource.
Each resource can be transformed many times \emph{within} the economy.
Timber might become 2$\times$4s, or plywood, or toothpicks, or mulch.
Iron ore might become steel, then sheet metal, and then a toaster.
Water might be ice, a sports drink, or Play-Doh.
The process of pulling a resource into the economy is called ``extraction.''
Equation~\ref{eq:PCbalance} indicates that everything that is extracted is used
for productive purposes.


%..............................
\paragraph{Resource intensity of the economy}
%..............................

The \mft{R} term in Equation \ref{eq:IPARX} is the resource intensity of the economy.
$R$ is defined as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:R}
  \mft{R} \equiv \frac{\text{total resources extracted}}{\text{GDP}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
\mft{R} measures the total resources used by the economy to create a
total amount of economic output (measured by GDP).
Because the numerator and denominator of \mft{R} have different units,
\mft{R} is an \emph{intensity}.

Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} shows use rates of some natural resources,
aggregated into important categories of biomass, ores and industrial minerals, and 
construction minerals.
In 2005, the world economy used about 19 Gt of biomass, 6.7 Gt of ores and 
industrial minerals, and about 22 Gt of construction materials
to produce about \$81.5 trillion dollars of GDP. 
One Gt is 10$^9$~tonnes (or 10$^{12}$~kg) and a trillion dollars is \$10$^{12}$.
Thus, each dollar of GDP produced used about 0.23 kg of biomass, 
0.082 kg of ores and minerals, and 0.27 kg of construction materials. 
A full accounting of the resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}
yields a long list of numbers, like a huge grocery list,
each number giving the amount of a single resource needed to make \$1 of GDP. 
This chapter discusses sustainability implications for a few resources,
with energy providing the prime example of resource intensity of the economy. 

Resource intensity can be measured and quantified at the whole-economy level,
as in the examples above.
Alternatively, resource intensity can be quantified per economic sector.
Clearly, the manufacturing sector of the economy requires resources to function.
Raw materials (such as copper and minerals) are required to make
finished goods (such as sewing machines and mobile phones).
But all sectors, even the service sector, need resources.
Consider the simple example of a haircut.
The stylist arrives at the salon in a vehicle
(which requires iron ore, copper, and other natural resources to manufacture; 
perhaps refined liquid fuel to operate; and 
an atmosphere that is a source of oxygen and which absorbs CO$_2$ and water, the products of combustion).
The stylist uses electric clippers and a hairdryer during each appointment
(which require both natural resources to manufacture and electricity to operate).
You sit in a fancy chair 
(which contains metals and plastics) and
drive to and from the appointment
(on roads made of tar or cement).
There is no escaping the dependence on resources to run an economy, 
even in the service sector. 


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Strong and weak sustainability for resources}%% extraction and consumption}
\label{sec:strong_weak_sust}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

A significant sustainability challenge 
is extracting and consuming natural resources\index{resources!natural}
at a sustainable rate.
When considering the sustainability of resource extraction and consumption, 
we can use the views on sustainability introduced 
in Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}:
``strong'' and ``weak.''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Strong sustainability}\index{sustainability!strong}
\label{sec:resources_strong_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Resources can be classified as ``renewable''\index{resources!renewable} or
``nonrenewable,''\index{resources!nonrenewable}
based on their regeneration rates.\index{regeneration rate!of resources}
Resources, such as the Sun,
that are expected to exist for millennia 
are classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate quickly (on the order of decades), 
such as forests and other biomass,
are also classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate slowly or not at all, such as fossil fuels,
are classified as nonrenewable.

Whether or not a resource is renewable affects the sustainability of its 
extraction and consumption,
per definitions of strong and weak sustainability 
given in Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}.
A criterion for ``strong sustainability'' is 
extracting and consuming resources 
at rates slower than their natural regeneration rates.
Thus, \emph{any} consumption of a nonrewable resource is not strongly sustainable.

The economy, being society's metabolism,\index{economy!as society's metabolism}
depends on natural resources
for its survival.
Indeed, we can say that the economy \emph{runs} on natural resources.\index{resources!natural}
All goods and the infrastructure for all services depend on
manufactured objects of all types:
cars and the roads on which they travel, 
homes and the utilities that sustain life,
food and the refrigerators that maintain freshness,
toilets and the sewer systems that remove wastes.
Furthermore, the operation of all these systems requires energy, the master resource.

Although any raw material can be essential 
(and not economically substitutable) 
for a given product,
the European Commission maintains a list of Critical Raw Materials (CRMs)\index{materials!critical!raw}
with special importance 
across a wide range of industries;
see Table~\ref{tab:CRMs}.
Notice the \emph{large number} of resources considered ``critical.''
Energy is important for making an economy run but so are material resources.

Another interesting feature of Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} is the \emph{breadth of applications}; 
most of the critical materials are used throughout the economy.
A material may be critical to a region, to an economic sector, or to an economy as a whole 
because of breadth of application, supply vulnerability or volatility, 
or supply limits.

Each region or sector will have its own list of CRMs.
For example, the transition to a renewable energy future 
(Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition})
depends on a large number of critical materials, 
outlined in a recent International Energy Agency report~\cite{IEA:2021wt}.
The point isn't which materials are critical for any given economy or sector;
it's that all sectors of all economies depend upon a large number of raw materials.

