Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} 
shows that resource consumption is growing through time.
By the ``strong sustainability'' criterion,
\emph{any} extraction of
construction minerals, ores and industrial minerals, and fossil energy carriers
is unsustainable, because
we are extracting these materials at rates that are faster than their regeneration rates.
The fact that we are \emph{increasing} our rate of material extraction
means that we are running well afoul of the strong sustainability criterion
for these materials.
On the other hand,
extraction of biomass \emph{could} be sustainable if
the extraction rate is less than the regrowth rate.
Unfortunately, Figure~\ref{fig:per_gdp_material_use} shows that biomass extraction
is not scaling with GDP.
In fact, GDP growth is supported exclusively by unsustainable material extraction.

By the strong sustainability criterion, 
we live in an unsustainable world.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Weak sustainability}\index{sustainability!weak}
\label{sec:resources_weak_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

A weak sustainability criterion is that resources are extracted slowly enough
to invent and deploy substitute(s) at scale before the resource is depleted.
A similar weak sustainability criterion can be established for waste:
wastes should be emitted slowly enough for their accumulation in the environment
to pose no problems before remediation technologies can be invented and deployed
at scale to dispose of the wastes.
A time horizon is needed for evaluating the weak sustainability criterion,
typically 50 years.
Thus, extraction of a resource is weakly sustainable so long as
the remaining stock is sufficient to last 50 years at today's extraction rate
(and, possibly expected future extraction rates).
And emission of wastes is weakly sustainable so long as 
remediation technologies will be deployed 
to ameliorate the wastes within 50 years.

To evaluate whether extraction of a resource meets the weak sustainability criterion,
the following steps can be performed.
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Establish the virgin material stock as of today, 
        often called the ``reserves'' of the resource.

  \item Divide the virgin stock by 50 years to obtain the average maximum weakly
        sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

  \item Find the current rate of extraction and suitably adjust 
        for any future increases or decreases~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).

  \item Compare the weakly sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
        and the current or future extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).
        If the current or future extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!) is greater than
        the average maximum weakly sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$),
        consumption of the resource does not meet the weak sustainability criterion.

\end{enumerate}
%
A similar approach can be used for wastes, like CO$_2$.
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Establish the amount of waste in the environment, the maximum allowable
        amount of waste in the environment as of today, and the 
        rate at which the ecosystem renders the waste inert.
  
  \item Establish the ``budget'' for waste emission by subtracting the 
        amount of waste in the environment from the maximum allowable waste in the environment. 
        
  \item Divide the budget by 50 years and subtract the rate at which the ecosystem renders the waste inert.
        The result is the maximum allowable waste emission rate
        for weak sustainability~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

  \item Find the current rate of waste emission and suitably adjust 
        for any future increases or decreases~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).

  \item Compare the weakly sustainable emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
        and the current or future emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).
        If the current or future emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!) is greater than
        the average maximum weakly sustainable emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$),
        emissions of the waste do not meet the weak sustainability criterion.

\end{enumerate}

The parameter $\rho$ quantifies the current extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
as a percentage above (positive)
or below (negative)
the average maximum weakly sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

\begin{equation} \label{eq:perc_above_ws}
  \rho \equiv \frac{\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}} - \mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}}{\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}} \times \text{100}
\end{equation}
%
A positive value for $\rho$ indicates the percentage by which the extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
is \emph{above} the average maximum weakly sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$). 
A negative value for $\rho$ indicates the percentage by which the extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
is \emph{below} the average maximum weakly sustainable extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$). 
A value for $\rho$ of 100\% means that the resource is being extracted at \emph{twice} 
its average maximum weakly sustainable extraction rate.
(Alternatively, $\rho$ = 100\% means that the resource would be exhausted in 25~years, 
not 50~years.)

Figure~\ref{fig:PercentageOfSustainable} shows the result of applying
