\section{Recycling and substitution}
\label{sec:recycling}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Two ways to become more sustainable are recycling and substitution.
Recycling\index{recycling} is a way to extend the usable life
of natural resources and
reduce rates of resource extraction.
Recycling uses discarded products as feedstock
to regenerate usable products.
Examples include paper recycling to pulp and glass recycling to new containers.
However, recycling requires energy
and other natural resources
for transporting used material to recycling centers and 
processing used material into recycled products.
For example, paper recycling uses water for cleaning and de-inking processes.
Glass recycling requires high-temperature heat for melting processes.
Whether recycling is, itself, a sustainable means of producing usable products
depends on the strong or weak sustainability of the recycling process.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Economist Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen proposed a fourth law of thermodynamics,
stating that complete recycling of matter is impossible~\cite{Georgescu-Roegen:1986aa}
because material resources are subject to irreversible degradation.
(Georgescu-Roegen was arguing by analogy from the second law of thermodynamics,
which states that all forms of energy are subject to irreversible degradation.)
Later, physicist and economist Robert Ayres correctly
argued that the second law of thermodynamics applies only to energy
(not to materials) and that
a stable, steady-state recycling system could exist
provided that two conditions are met:
(a)~a large stockpile of waste material exists 
    (so energy to obtain the waste material is small) and
(b)~an exogenous source, such as the sun, supplies energy freely and
    at sufficient rate for reprocessing of discarded material~\cite{Ayres:1999}.

The importance of energy to recycling is evident,
even in a debate about the viability of recycling!

\end{mcframe}

Substitution in manufacturing or production is the process of replacing
use of a valuable, scarce, or nonrenewable resource
with a less valuable, less scarce, or renewable resource%
\footnote{
  For a related discussion of substitution,
  see Q\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.\ref{question:consumption_substitution}.
}.
Replacing use of a scarce resource with use of an abundant resource
typically extends the time horizon for depleting manufacturing feedstocks and
brings us closer to weak sustainability.

Scarce resources tend to be valuable.
Abundant resources tend to be less valuable.
Using an abundant resource instead of a scarce resource therefore typically
makes sense from a cost perspective.
However, substitution is possible only when the two resources in question
are identical or nearly identical
such that they can serve the same purpose in a manufacturing or production environment.
Examples of substitution include:
replacing coated steel (expensive) automobile interior parts with
injection-molded plastics (inexpensive),
replacing Styrofoam hamburger containers (nonrenewable)
with paper or cardboard wrappings (renewable), and
use of solar electricity (renewable) instead of coal electricity (nonrenewable).
Switching from consuming nonrenewable resources
to consuming renewable resources
is an important aspect of sustainability, 
for both the weak \emph{and} the strong versions%
\footnote{
  In some cases, renewable resources still have environmental impacts.
  For example, biomass is a renewable energy source, 
  but burning wood can lead to reduced air quality.
}.

That said, there are important limits to substitutability.
At a manufacturing plant, the type of electricity
(for example, coal electricity\index{electricity!coal} or solar electricity\index{electricity!solar})
is immaterial,
so long as both options are (for the U.S.) 120 V at 60 Hz.
From the point of view of the manufacturing plant, coal electricity and solar electricity are 
perfect substitutes.
However, at the point of electricity generation, 
the feedstocks for electricity production are \emph{not} substitutes.
Coal-fired Rankine cycle\index{Rankine cycle} power plants
cannot use the Sun's energy to make electricity.
Similarly, a pile of coal is useless
to solar photovoltaic\index{solar photovoltaic electricity} farms.

Sometimes a scarce (and expensive), renewable resource is replaced by a
less-expensive, nonrenewable alternative.
Two examples illustrate.
The first example involves ocean-going vessels.
In the sailing age, ships were made of timber, with teak and mahogany being
favored ship-building woods.
Today, cargo ships are made of steel, and pleasure craft are made almost exclusively
of glass-fiber reinforced polymer composites, both of which are non-renewable materials.
Teak and mahogany, despite being renewable,
are now too rare and too expensive for shipbuilding,
both in terms of material cost and
labor cost.
As often happens, the ready availability of less-expensive vessels
means that many more boats are purchased and used.
The second example involves lighting.
Societies moved away from wax candles and whale oil lanterns to
``town gas,'' kerosene, and finally, electric lights.

In both cases (ships and lights), none of the options
(wood ships, steel ships,
wax candles, whale oil lanterns, kerosene lanterns, or electric lights)
meets the strong sustainability criterion.
However, all of wood ships, wax candles, whale oil lanterns, town gas lamps, and
kerosene lamps proved to be weakly sustainable.
We found substitutes for the natural resources
in a reasonable time frame and
before the natural resources were depleted.
(See Q5.\ref{question:weak_sust_good_enough}
for discussion of whether weak sustainability is ``good enough.'')


