\section{Energy as the prime example}
\label{sec:energy_as_prime_example}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

It has been argued
(as we do in Section~\ref{sec:masterE})
that energy is
the master resource~\cite{library1971energy}\index{energy!as master resource}
for two important reasons.
First, energy is required
for extraction of all natural resources (including energy itself),
for any material transformation,
for consuming goods and services, and
for disposing of goods.
Second, energy is fungible.
Within the limits of the second law of thermodynamics,
energy in one form can be converted to energy in another form
using machines.
An automobile converts chemical potential energy (gasoline)
to kinetic energy (car motion).
A hairdryer converts electricity (from the grid)
to heat (applied to hair).
A solar panel converts solar energy (from the sun)
to electricity (for use in many devices, including, possibly, hair dryers).

Because energy is the master resource,\index{energy!as master resource}
we use energy as the prime example in the IPARX equation (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}).
There are two important questions:
where are we using energy, and
are we using energy sustainably?
Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} answers the first question
for the U.S.
Energy is used in four broad sectors of the economy:
residences, commerce, industry, and transportation.
Industry and transportation use more energy than residences and commerce.

