\section{Energy intensity of the economy ($\mft{R}_{\mft{Ep}}$)}
\label{sec:energy_intensity_of_the_economy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Continuing the \href{https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/explication}{explication}
of the IPARX identity,
one piece or facet of resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}
is the primary energy intensity ($R_{Ep}$) of the world economy.
$R_{Ep}$ is the amount of primary energy required to create one unit (dollar) of
world GDP.
Of course, many other resources are \emph{also} required to create a unit of GDP,
but we use energy as the prime example of an important resource in the economy.
The primary energy intensity of the economy is formed
by dividing primary energy consumption ($E_p$)
by world GDP,
that is, dividing the line in Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}
by the line in Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus}.
The result is Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus}.

