Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus} shows that
the primary energy intensity of the world economy ($R_{Ep}$) has fallen from
15 to 4~MJ/2017 international dollar across the last two centuries.
The decline is caused by the fact that the world economy's GDP
(Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus})
has been growing at a faster rate (in \%/year terms) than primary energy consumption
(Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}).
The decline indicates that each additional dollar of GDP
is created with incrementally less energy consumption.

While the decrease in $R_{Ep}$ (the prime example for \mft{R} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX})
appears to be good news for sustainability
(declining \mft{R} puts downward pressure on \mft{I} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}), 
Figure~\ref{fig:per_gdp_material_use} shows that (on a per-mass basis)
the largest decreases in primary energy per GDP are coming from declining consumption
of biomass.
Ironically, the decreases in \mft{R} are coming from reduction in per-GDP consumption 
of a type of energy that is possibly sustainable, biomass!

We can use these data to learn something about the IPARX terms
(Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}) and CO$_2$ emissions.
A narrowed version of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX},
considers only CO$_2$ emissions on the left-hand side of the equation
and the energy intensity of the economy ($R_{Ep}$) instead of \mft{R} on the right-hand side.
When $R_{Ep}$ falls, downward pressure is placed on CO$_2$ emissions.
Whether CO$_2$ emissions \emph{actually} decrease
depends on the rates of increase or decline of the other terms
on the right side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph} shows that CO$_2$ emissions have been growing over time.
So, other terms on the right side of the IPARX identity
are growing faster than energy intensity of the economy is declining;
see Section~\ref{sec:revisit_IPARX}.


