\section{Patterns of resource extraction and resource transitions}
\label{sec:resource_transitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Extraction of finite resources
(such as coal, oil, natural gas, lithium, neodymium, phosphorous, or helium)
follows a pattern through time.
In the beginning, extraction of a useful but finite resource accelerates
as demand climbs and technologies are developed to reduce the cost of extraction.
Through time, the resource extraction rate peaks then and declines.
A clear example of a production curve for a finite resource is
extraction of coal in the UK, shown in Figure~\ref{fig:UK_coal_extraction}.

<<UK_coal_extraction, fig.scap="UK coal production", fig.cap="UK coal production. \\emph{Sources}: \\citet{Rutledge:2011, Rutledge:tv} for 1830--2009; \\citet{UK_dept_BEIS:2021} for 2010--2020.">>=
uk_coal_extraction <- readxl::read_excel(file.path("chapters", "ch05-ResourceIntensity", "datasets", "CoalGraph.xlsx"),
                                         sheet = "data to plot") %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    Year = as.numeric(Year)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::filter(
    complete.cases(.)
  )

uk_coal_extraction %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year, y = UK_coal_production_Mt)) +
  ggplot2::geom_line(size = 1, colour = mc_title_blue) +

  ggplot2::labs(x = ggplot2::element_blank(),
                y = "UK coal production [Mt/year]") +

  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

The cumulative production of a limited resource follows a logistic curve,
with an inflection point (from concave upward to concave downward)
at the production peak
and leveling toward the end;
see Figure~\ref{fig:UK_coal_logistic}.

<<UK_coal_logistic, fig.scap="UK coal production logistic curve", fig.cap="UK coal production logistic curve. \\emph{Sources}: \\citet{Rutledge:2011, Rutledge:tv}, 1829--2009; own calculations, 2010--2020.">>=
uk_coal_extraction %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year, y = q_Gt)) +
  ggplot2::geom_line(size = 1, colour = mc_title_blue) +

  ggplot2::labs(x = ggplot2::element_blank(),
                y = "UK coal cumulative production [Gt]") +

  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

In the case of the UK, substitution away from coal for electricity generation 
is occurring. 
Coal production is now dominated by China, India, the U.S., and Australia
and international trade is possible.
So the world will not face coal shortages
until all regions are exhausted of the resource.
Each region is at different places on its logistic curve
for resource production.
Other ways to substitute away from coal for electricity 
include deploying natural gas, wind, and solar electricity generation, 
as the UK is doing now.

One way to slow down the inevitable march of time
along logistic curves for finite resources is to transition
economies to use fewer resources per unit of GDP produced,
that is to reduce the resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}.
Reduction of resource intensity of the economy is sometimes called \emph{dematerialization}.
Reducing \mft{R} will reduce resource consumption but only if
GDP stays constant or grows more slowly than the
rate at which \mft{R} decreases.

For the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions,
reducing \mft{R} means reducing the energy intensity of economic activity
($R_{Ep}$),
that is, reducing the amount of energy required to produce
each unit of GDP.
(Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition} discusses a distinct but related issue,
transitioning the energy system to reduce CO$_2$ emissions
from each unit of energy consumed.)

There are many ways often suggested to reduce the energy intensity of economic activity ($R_{Ep}$).
First, increasing energy efficiency (through efficiency standards or mandates)
can decrease the energy consumption for end uses.
Examples include corporate average fuel economy (CAFE) standards for vehicles
in the U.S.\
and mandates for LED lighting in many countries.
Another way to reduce the energy intensity of an economy is to move
away from a manufacturing economy toward a service economy.
However, as shown in the haircut example at the beginning of this chapter,
the need for resources never goes away, even in a service economy.
In fact, moving to a service economy often introduces problem-shifting
(Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles}),
as finished goods are imported and manufacturing moves off shore~\cite{Hardt:2018aa}.

 
