\begin{questions}

  \item Some aquifers, such as the Ogallala aquifer, are called ``fossil water''
        because they were filled with glacial melt from the last ice age.
        Is using any such resource sustainable?
        What are the moral and ethical implications of leaving a valuable and
        usable resource \emph{unused}?

  \item What is the purpose (\emph{telos}) of mineral resources in the environment?
        Should they be left in place or used?
        Humans are the only creatures on Earth that make use of most minerals.
        What are some positive impacts on animal populations that arise from
        humans' use of materials that are not available to any other animal?
        Are there any?

  \item What are the positive features of the strong sustainability criterion?
        What are the weaknesses of the strong sustainability criterion?
        Is the strong sustainability criterion too severe for modern life today?
        Justify your answer.
        Can strong sustainability be applied selectively to some resources but
        not others or should all resources be judged equally?
        What are the implications of not applying the strong sustainability
        criterion universally to all resources?

  \item Why is the weak sustainability criterion a good criterion?
        What are the drawbacks to weak sustainability criteria?
        What is the basis for your judgement?

  \item In which circumstances is a weak sustainability criterion appropriate?
        In which circumstances is the strong sustainability criterion appropriate?
        Is weak sustainability good enough?
        Give examples.\label{question:weak_sust_good_enough}

  \item Time is our most constrained resource. The human lifespan is about 4000 weeks.
        How do you use your time?
        What fraction of your total time is devoted to
        economically productive activities? Why?
        What are the sustainability impacts of how you spend your time?
        Can you quantify the sustainability impacts of how you spend your time
        in terms of the IPARX equation?

  \item Where does your water come from?
        How does it get to you? Where is your waste water treated?
        How is energy, the master resource, involved in each of these steps?
        How has water provision changed over time where you live?

  \item Evaluate the notion of a closed-loop water system (so called ``toilet-to-tap'').
        Would you drink water from a toilet-to-tap system?
        Does your answer change if you learn that, already, there are low levels
        of many pharmaceutical substances and organic pollutants in drinking water?
        A closed-loop water system would probably lower exposure to some pollutants
        and increase concentrations of pharmaceutical substances (or else require
        more advanced waste-water treatment technology).
        How does a closed-loop system affect sustainability for communities that
        use it? Other communities?

  \item Carbon-driven global climate change and population growth are making
        desalination of seawater a more prominent source of water for
        many populations.
        Carbon emissions from desalination may increase from 76 million
        tons of CO$_2$ per year in 2015 to 200-500 million tons per year by 2040
        \cite{GCWDA2015}.
