\begin{projects}

  \item Update the weak sustainability calculations of Figure~\ref{fig:WeakSustEnergyGraph}
        using the latest data from
        the U.S.\ Energy Information Agency (EIA)~\cite{U.S.-Energy-Information-Agency:tr}.

  \item Update the weak sustainability calculations of Figure~\ref{fig:WeakSustEnergyGraph},
        taking into account projected additions to reserves into the future.
        Do the weak sustainability estimates
        of Figure~\ref{fig:WeakSustEnergyGraph} change?

  \item Choose a material (not germanium or zinc)
        from the European Commission list of critical raw materials in Table~\ref{tab:CRMs}.
        Do today's consumption rates of that material meet weak or strong sustainability criteria?
        Provide suggestions for ways to bring consumption rates closer to strong sustainability.

  \item Research the source locations for the materials in Table~\ref{tab:CRMs}.
        How would you characterize the geographic distribution of critical raw material sourcing?
        Localized? Global? Other?
        What are the sustainability (environmental, economic, and social) implications
        of the geographical distribution of critical raw material sources?

  \item Compare the weak sustainability approach
        to the methods of David Rutledge~\cite{Rutledge:tv}\index{Rutledge, David}.
        Which produces better estimates of the time to exhaust nonrenewable resources?
        Why?

  \item Visit a recycling center and assess its sustainability.
        Is the center an example of strong sustainability, weak sustainability, or neither?
        Where is are the recycling processes consuming energy or other materials?
        Is the energy fossil-based or renewable?

  \item Research the CAFE automobile efficiency standards in the U.S.\ and
        other automobile efficiency standards worldwide.
        Evaluate the strategies, tactics, and approaches to improving fuel economy in automobiles and trucks.
        Which approach works best?
        Which approaches are ineffective?
        Why?

  \item Evaluate the ecological and economic impacts substitution of an
        injection-molded plastic part for a stamped steel part on an automobile.
        What are the raw material and extraction implications?
        How much energy is used to create the part?
        Does using a lighter part have energy implications over the life of the
        vehicle?
        Are there issues with corrosion or UV exposure?
        Are there disposal or recycling issues?
        In your view, which material is more environmentally friendly?
        Where do you get data to answer these questions?
        Where do you draw boundaries?
        How do you evaluate tradeoffs?
        
  \item In winter, fresh food is transported from warm locations (for example, California and Florida)
        to cold locations (Michigan, for instance), consuming fossil fuels
        and causing CO$_2$ emissions.
        Alternatively, LED lighting could be used at indoor farms to grow food
        in cold climates in the winter.
        Assess the benefits and drawbacks of the LED approach relative to the 
        shipping approach. 
        When would it make sense from a sustainability point of view to grow locally using LEDs?
        When is it more sustainable to transport food from warm to cold climates?

\end{projects}

